                <html:p>For any two sets <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, we may form the <html:em><html:strong>full <fr:link href="/jms-00I7/" title="Relation" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00I7/" display-uri="jms-00I7" type="local">relation</fr:link></html:strong></html:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (A\times  B\right )\mathclose {}}\colon  A\mathbin {\nrightarrow } B]]></fr:tex>, also called the <html:em><html:strong>total <fr:link href="/jms-00I7/" title="Relation" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00I7/" display-uri="jms-00I7" type="local">relation</fr:link></html:strong></html:em>, so that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\mathrel {{\mathopen {}\left (A\times  B\right )\mathclose {}}}b]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  B]]></fr:tex>. In other words, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (A\times  B\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> is the <html:em>total</html:em> subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\times  B]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
